<BaseLayout title="Caring for your dialysis access" description="Your fistula or catheter is your lifeline. How the types of access differ, how to care for yours at home, and the warning signs to act on.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Caring for your dialysis access</h1>
      <p class="lead">Your access is your lifeline for every session — protecting it protects you.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <p>Hemodialysis needs a fast blood flow — about 300–500 mL per minute — that ordinary veins can't
      provide. Your <strong>access</strong> is the connection between your body and the machine. Without a
      working access, dialysis can't happen, so caring for it is one of the most important things you can do.</p>

      <h2>The three types</h2>
      <ul style="line-height:1.9">
        <li><strong>AV fistula</strong> — an artery joined to a vein; the safest, longest-lasting option, and the goal for most patients.</li>
        <li><strong>AV graft</strong> — a soft tube joining artery to vein; used when veins aren't suitable for a fistula.</li>
        <li><strong>Catheter</strong> — a tube into a large vein; useful early on, but the highest risk of infection and clotting, so it's removed once a fistula or graft is ready.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Caring for a fistula at home</h2>
      <ul style="line-height:1.9">
        <li>Keep it clean, and wash the arm before each session.</li>
        <li>Feel for the gentle buzz (the “thrill”) each day — it tells you it's flowing.</li>
        <li>On that arm: <strong>no</strong> blood-pressure cuffs, no blood draws, no tight sleeves or watches, and avoid heavy lifting or sleeping on it.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="notice"><strong>Call your center right away if:</strong> you can't feel the thrill; the area
      is red, painful, warm or swollen; you have a fever; or there's bleeding that won't stop.</div>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Ask us about your access</a></p>
